          "body": "The Meribah narrative (20:2-13) is one of the most carefully constructed episodes in the Pentateuch. God's command is precise (20:8): take the rod, assemble the congregation, speak to the rock. Moses's departure is threefold: he speaks to the people in anger rather than speaking to the rock (20:10); he attributes the miracle to himself and Aaron ('shall we bring forth water?' 20:10); and he strikes the rock twice rather than speaking (20:11). The water still comes — abundantly. This is the pastoral sting: the visible ministry succeeded. The congregation drank. An outside observer would have called it a triumph. But God evaluates the posture of the heart, not the visible outcome. His verdict (20:12) identifies the root failure as unbelief — 'you have not believed Me' — expressing itself in failure to treat Him as holy before the people. As Swindoll notes, it is precisely at the moment of greatest familiarity with divine power that the leader is most vulnerable to treating God as a means to an end rather than as the Holy One to be honored."
