          "body": "God's verdict in 20:12 is two-layered and indivisible. The first charge is inward: 'you have not believed Me.' The second is outward: 'to treat Me as holy in the sight of the sons of Israel.' These are not two sins but one sin in two dimensions. Unbelief in Moses's heart expressed itself as a performance of divine power that centered Moses's frustration rather than God's character. The congregation saw Moses's anger, heard Moses's accusation ('you rebels'), and watched Moses strike the rock — when they should have heard Moses speak to the rock in quiet confidence and watched water appear from a word. The 'sight of the sons of Israel' (20:12) is the public-representational dimension of leadership: what the congregation perceives God to be like is shaped by how His servants display Him. John Calvin's reading is precise here: Moses did not deny God's power but disrupted the intended picture of how God acts — with word, not force; with grace, not wrath."
