        "excerpt": "Because you have not believed Me, to treat Me as holy in the sight of the sons of Israel, therefore you shall not bring this assembly into the land which I have given them.",
        "body": "The opening verse of Numbers 20 buries Miriam in a single clause and moves on. The terseness is intentional — she receives no mourning period recorded here (contrast Aaron's thirty days, 20:29), no narrative eulogy, no cause of death. One verse, and the prophetess of the Exodus is gone. The congregation's immediate response is not grief but complaint (20:2-5), which suggests the text is less concerned with Miriam's death in itself than with what follows: the crisis that will cost Moses and Aaron everything.\n\nGod's command to Moses in 20:8 is grammatically precise. Take the rod. Assemble the congregation. Speak to the rock. The rod is a tool of authorization (Aaron's budded rod, stored before the Lord — Numbers 17:10), not a tool of percussion. The act of speech before the congregation will display God's word as sufficient — no force required. Moses's departure from this command is threefold: he addresses the congregation in anger ('you rebels,' 20:10), he shifts agency to himself and Aaron ('shall we bring forth water?' 20:10), and he strikes the rock — twice (20:11). The water comes anyway. This is the chapter's sharpest irony: the miracle vindicates nothing about Moses's posture. God's power is not the variable.\n\nGod's verdict in 20:12 is carefully worded. The charge is not incompetence, not accidental deviation, but **unbelief** — 'you have not believed Me.' The unbelief expressed itself in failure to treat God as holy before the people. Timothy Ashley (*The Book of Numbers*, NICOT, 1993) notes that the Hebrew phrase 'to treat as holy' (*leqaddeshu*) does not mean Moses denied God's existence or power, but that his conduct before the congregation failed to display God's character accurately. The people saw an angry leader striking rock; they should have seen a trusting servant speaking God's word.\n\nThe etiological note of 20:13 is a formal closing device that simultaneously names two things: the place ('Meribah,' from riv — to quarrel) and the theological outcome — 'He proved Himself holy among them.' The same root *qadash* appears in both verse 12 (Moses failed to treat God as holy) and verse 13 (God proved Himself holy). Human failure does not finally prevent God's holiness from being vindicated; it only changes who bears the cost.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ya'an... laken* — 'because... therefore' (20:12): the standard Hebrew causal-consequential construction. *Leqaddeshu* — Hiphil infinitive of *qadash*: 'to cause to be treated as holy,' 'to sanctify Him.' *Merivah* — from the root *riv* (to contend, to quarrel at law); both this Meribah and the earlier one at Rephidim (Exodus 17:7) use the same root."
